  "tool_calls": [
    {
      "name": "Bash",
      "args": {
        "command": "cat stm32-project.jsonc 2>/dev/null || echo \"NO_DESCRIPTOR\"",
        "description": "Check project descriptor for ELF and device family"
      }
    },
    {
      "name": "Bash",
      "args": {
        "command": "stm32 prog list-probes",
        "description": "List attached ST-LINK probes"
      }
    },
    {
      "name": "Bash",
      "args": {
        "command": "STM32_PROGRAMMER_DEFAULT_SN=066DFF485754727567021514 stm32 debug start --no-halt",
        "description": "Attach debug session to running L476RG target without halting"
      }
    }
  ],
  "final_text": "Two probes are on the bench, so I'll pin the L476RG probe (the descriptor's board) and attach without halting:\nAttached without halting \u2014 the target is still running.\n\n- **Probe**: ST-LINK `066DFF\u20261514` (NUCLEO-L476RG, pinned explicitly since the N6570-DK probe is also attached)\n- **ELF**: autodiscovered `\u2026/BLINKY/STM32CubeIDE/Debug/BLINKY.elf`\n- **gdbserver** PID 149480 / **gdb** PID 149486 on port 61234\n- **Target state**: `running` (not halted)\n\nNote this was a one-shot `start` \u2014 it verifies the attach path and tears down. For follow-up reads on the live target (variables, peripherals, callstack), the read-style recipes (`read-peripheral`, `snapshot`, etc.) also attach without reset and halt only momentarily; if you want a persistent multi-step session, that goes through the Python `DebugSession` context manager instead."
}